Abstract — Air pollution has become a serious issue affecting
both the environment and human health, particularly in urban and
industrial regions[1]. Many current pollution monitoring systems
focus only on measuring environmental conditions and reporting
them once pollution levels exceed safe limits. These systems do
not provide predictive capabilities or automatic control actions.
In this study, a new system called SL-PCG (Self-Learning
Pollution Control Grid) is proposed [4]. It is an AI-based system
designed to predict pollution levels and automatically control
environmental conditions before they become harmful. The system
integrates environmental data collection, time-series forecasting
techniques, rule-based control actions, and a feedback-based
learning mechanism. The model uses both simulated and real-time
sensor data such as AQI, temperature, humidity, and traffic density
to detect short-term pollution trends [2]. By analyzing these
environmental parameters, the system can predict potential
increases in pollution levels ahead of time. If the predicted values
reach or exceed predefined safety limits, the system automatically
activates pollution control methods such as ventilation or air
filtration systems.
The experimental results demonstrate that the proposed system
improves response time and reduces the severity of pollution
spikes compared to conventional monitoring approaches [8]. Early
intervention helps maintain a more balanced and stable
environmental condition [5]. The system is also scalable and can
be integrated with IoT devices, making it suitable for smart city
infrastructure, industrial environments, and institutional areas like
university campuses.
Keywords — Artificial Intelligence, Pollution Monitoring, IoT
Systems, Time-Series Prediction, Smart Cities, Environmental
Control, Intelligent Systems.
